      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Child's Space</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Sally Mendel (Citizens' Committee for Children of New York) says lack of space for preschool programs in New York City (Sept 5 article) is result of government's failure to allocate enough money for school construction</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Preschool, a Wealth of Benefits and a Dearth of Space'' (news article, Sept. 5):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Preschool, a Wealth of Benefits and a Dearth of Space'' (news article, Sept. 5):</p>
        <p>Over the last few years two important initiatives were begun by the New York State Legislature without enough financing. Consequently, both the universal prekindergarten program and the reduced class size program for kindergarten through third grades are in jeopardy.</p>
        <p>These programs are part of a preventive strategy for reducing school failure and providing experiences that promote better outcomes for all children. In addition, the support services provided to families in the schools through community-based organizations are also endangered because of lack of space.</p>
        <p>The classroom space issue is a result of government's failure to allocate enough money for school construction.</p>
        <p>SALLY MENDEL  New York, Sept. 7, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is vice president, Citizens' Committee for Children of New York.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
